\title{Branch Support Command}
\description{
An \link[R6:R6Class]{R6} class that configures the calculation of branch
(Bremer) support values in \pkg{nitro}.

\code{BranchSupportCommand} implements the suboptimal sampling approach
described by Goloboff et al. (2008): starting from an optimal-length
tree, branch swapping is performed repeatedly while progressively
increasing the number of suboptimal steps accepted, filling the tree
buffer at each step. Once the suboptimal sampling loop is complete,
the buffer is flushed via \link{KeepTreesCommand} and the optimal trees are
reloaded from a \link{ReadTreesCommand}. TNT then calculates the minimum
score difference required to lose each group with the \code{bsupport}
command.
}
\details{
\subsection{Dependencies}{

\code{BranchSupportCommand} requires three dependencies to be resolved
before the command can be enqueued:
\itemize{
\item \code{"starting trees"} (required) — a \link{ReadTreesCommand} object
providing the optimal trees to reload into the buffer after
suboptimal sampling is complete. Supplied automatically by
\code{\link[=execute_analysis]{execute_analysis()}} via the \code{starting_trees} argument.
\item \code{"tree search"} (required) — a \link{BranchBreakingCommand} object
defining the branch swapping strategy used during suboptimal tree
sampling. The command is automatically set to \code{set_only = TRUE} so
that it configures the search without executing it immediately.
\item \code{"tree buffer"} (required) — a \link{TreeBufferCommand} object defining
the maximum number of trees to retain. The buffer size is
redistributed proportionally across the suboptimal steps during
enqueuing.
}

All three dependencies are resolved automatically when the command is
attached to a \link{TreeAnalysis} via \code{\link[=set_support]{set_support()}} and the analysis is
run via \code{\link[=execute_analysis]{execute_analysis()}}.
}

\subsection{Queue integration}{

Calling \verb{$enqueue()} adds this command to a \link{CommandQueue} at priority
\code{503}. When \verb{$method} is \code{"suboptimal_sampling"}, the enqueue method
also adds:
\itemize{
\item A staged sequence of \link{SuboptimalCommand}, \link{TreeBufferCommand}, and
\link{BranchBreakingCommand} entries at priority \code{502} — one round per
value in \verb{$suboptimal_steps} — with the buffer size redistributed
proportionally across steps.
\item A \link{KeepTreesCommand} at priority \code{504} that flushes the buffer after
the suboptimal loop completes.
\item A \link{ReadTreesCommand} at priority \code{505} that reloads the optimal
trees, ensuring that \code{bsupport} compares against the correct set of
trees.
}
}

\subsection{Command output}{

\verb{$render()} produces a \code{bsupport} command of the form:
\itemize{
\item Absolute index: \verb{bsupport =<group_collapse_value>;}
\item Relative index: \verb{bsupport [=<group_collapse_value>;}
}
}

